==English==

===Etymology===
The saying comes from the 1866 [[w:Dion Boucicault|Dion Boucicault]] play, ''Flying Scud'', in which a character knowingly breezes past a difficult situation saying, "Excuse me Mr. Quail, I can't stop; I've got to see a man about a dog."

===Verb===
{{infl|en|verb|head=to [[see]] a [[man]] about a [[horse]]}}

# {{slang|idiomatic|euphemism}} A message signaling one needs to [[urinate]] (''used mainly of men'')
#: ''Wait for me here. I'll only be a couple of minutes. I've just got to '''see a man about a horse'''.''
# {{slang|idiomatic|euphemism}} A message signaling one needs to go missing for a short while, for any reason, without giving a real explanation.

====Quotations====
